Utterance: Hi, Ellie!
Hi! It’s great to see you again. How has the past week been?
It’s been okay. I actually followed through with the study plan!
That’s fantastic! How did it go?
I managed to finish the research and outline, and I’m halfway through writing the paper.
Wow, that’s impressive! How did you feel during the process?
I felt less anxious than before, which was nice.
That’s wonderful to hear! What do you think made the difference?
I think breaking it down into smaller tasks helped a lot.
Absolutely! It’s a great strategy. Did you find time for breaks?
I did! I went for walks and watched a couple of shows.
That’s excellent! It’s important to recharge. How did that affect your productivity?
I think it helped me focus better when I returned to studying.
Fantastic! What about your sleep? Have you tried any relaxation techniques?
Yes, I started doing the deep breathing exercises before bed.
How has that worked for you?
I think it’s helped a bit, but I still wake up feeling tired.
It’s a step in the right direction. Have you discussed your sleep issues further with your doctor?
I have an appointment next week to talk about it.
That’s good to hear. Remember, it’s important to advocate for your health.
I will. I want to feel better.
Absolutely! You deserve to feel good. Have you noticed any changes in your mood lately?
I think I feel a little more positive.
That’s great! What do you think contributed to that change?
Probably finishing parts of the paper and having some good moments with friends.
That’s wonderful! Social connections can really boost our mood.
Yeah, I reached out to a friend for help, and it felt good.
That’s a big step! How did that conversation go?
It went really well! She was really supportive.
I’m so glad to hear that. It sounds like you’re building a stronger support system.
I hope so. I want to keep reaching out.
That’s a great goal. Is there anyone else you’d like to connect with?
I’ve been thinking about talking to my family more.
That’s a wonderful idea. What holds you back from connecting with them?
I guess I feel like they wouldn’t understand what I’m going through.
It’s common to feel that way. Have you considered sharing your feelings with them?
I haven’t, but maybe I should try.
It might help strengthen your relationship. Even if they don’t fully understand, they can still offer support.
That makes sense.
How about we set a goal for you to reach out to one family member this week?
I can do that.
Great! What else would you like to focus on during our session today?
I want to talk about my feelings of being down sometimes.
Of course. Can you tell me more about those feelings?
Sometimes I just feel really low, even when things are going well.
It’s okay to feel that way. Are there specific triggers that you’ve noticed?
I think it’s just the combination of my health issues and feeling overwhelmed.
That’s understandable. It’s a lot to carry. Have you found any coping mechanisms that help?
I try to distract myself with activities, but it doesn’t always work.
Distraction can be a temporary relief. How about incorporating more activities that bring you joy?
I’d like that. I’ve been meaning to try painting again.
That sounds like a wonderful idea! Art can be very therapeutic.
I used to enjoy it a lot.
Let’s set a goal for you to spend some time painting this week.
Yes, I’ll make time for that.
Perfect! As we wrap up, what’s one thing you’d like to take away from today’s session?
I want to focus on reaching out to family and making time for painting.
Those are excellent goals. I’m proud of you for taking these steps.
Thanks, Ellie.
You’re doing great! I look forward to hearing about your progress next time.
Me too!
Goodbye for now.
Bye!
